         <abstract>
            <p>Votes on bills to ban or to tax futures transactions are examined to identify sources of regional opposition to futures markets and exchanges. Opposition to futures markets was located in the grain-producing states but has moderated over time. The second part of the paper measures the effect of the jurisdictional conflict and subsequent accommodation between the Commodity Futures Trading Commission and the Securities and Exchange Commission on membership seat prices on the Chicago Board of Trade, Chicago Mercantile Exchange, and the Chicago Board of Options Exchange.</p>
         </abstract>
